Subject: Asynchronous Circuit Design



Dear Chris

Later than I expected, I have received two reviews of your proposal. Thanks for
your patience. I shall copy the relevant sections here and then continue
afterwards.

******************
Reviewer 1

I think that this book does fill a hole that exists.  Dr. Myers does a
reasonable job of presenting sufficient breadth and detail.  I do strongly
suggest that a section on synchronizers be included.  With this information, and
some improvement to the text as it is, I believe this would be a useful book for
those both in industry and academia.

*******************
Reviewer 2

As the author notes, there is no recent textbook on asynchronous design. The
book by Brzozoski and Seger gives a comprehensive and rigorous overview of the
subject, but is not written as a textbook.

 The scope of the book seems reasonable.  It is clearly written by someone in
the synthesis camp.  The focus on explaining the Huffman and Muller schools is a
reasonable one to take.

  In the prospectus, the author lists several current applications of
asynchronous circuits, including Intel's RAPPID (a research project) and
Philips's pager.  Myrinet's "pipeline synchronization" should be added to this
list.  It would be constructive to add a chapter to survey recent asynchronous
designs, both research projects and shipping products.  The U. Manchester Amulet
belongs here.  This should definitely be a separate chapter, as this material
will become dated faster than the rest of the content of the book.  Nonetheless,
I believe that adding examples of substantial designs will lend credibility to
the book.

  Another possible addition would be a chapter could with examples of mixed
synchronous/asynchronous designs such as self-resetting domino logic, pulse
logic ALU's, source synchronous communication.  The role of synchronization in
synchronous designs along with a discussion of metastability should be here.
There are still plenty of designers who don't really grasp what metastability is
about.  This chapter could include connections of asynchronous techniques to
"far-out" technologies such as RSFQ (superconducting) logic, etc.

  Now for comments on the three chapters (5-7) I examined.  I believe that the
use of running examples will make this material accessible to a wider audience.
On the other hand, I found the complete lack of theorems and proofs to be
disturbing.  The presentation is very "operational" -- it describes step-by-step
what each algorithms does, and the procedure for synthesis, but it doesn't give
me a sense that I know that it's correct. I just understand how it works for the
particular examples.  I hope that this can be corrected with some modest
revision.
  First, each of chapters five and six should clearly define the synthesis
problems that they address.  Synthesis is a function (in the mathematical sense)
whose domain is a specification (i.e. a flow table or a signal transition graph)
and whose range is a netlist.  These functions should be clearly defined.  Then,
the author can explain that one way to implement one of these functions is to
decompose it into three or four simpler functions (e.g. state minimization,
state assignment, and logic synthesis).  Each section that presents one of these
simpler functions can take a similar approach.  In the end, the detailed
algorithms can be presented in imperative pseudo-code (i.e. operational terms),
but a more functional/mathematical description of the high level problems would
help.  Theoretical results that justify key steps in the synthesis procedures
should be (in my opinion) marked with theorems.  To keep this text accessible,
to less theoretically orient readers, most proofs can be omitted 

