? a citation to
the relevant literature should do the job.  [BS95] provides much of the=
 theory
that is lacking in this text, and frequent citations would help cover t=
his gap.
I think an occasional proof is a fine idea, in particular when such a p=
roof is
short and contributes to understanding the bigger picture.  Pseudo-code=

fragments should include comments.  Of course, the detailed description=
 will be
in the text, but a few comments in the code can provide useful clues to=
 the
reader and make the connection to the text clearer.

  It would be helpful if the examples could be motivated by a "story pr=
oblem"
style example.  This is done nicely with the wine shop example in chapt=
er 7. The
examples in chapters 5 and 6 are more of the "consider this flow table"=
 or (STG)
style.  For readers not familiar with asynchronous design, the obvious =
question
is:
  "Why should I care about some made-up flow table? I want to know if I=
 can do
anything real with this stuff."
Motivating the examples with some, semi-plausible description of what t=
hey could
be used for helps enhance the readers intuition.  As I noted at the beg=
inning of
this paragraph, chapter 7 handles this well.

I liked chapter 7.  A comprehensive description of the authors POSET te=
chniques
is a good contribution.  This chapter should include descriptions of ot=
her
techniques such as timed automata (e.g. Kronos), Abadi and Lamports
"old-fashioned recipe", Pena's work on relative timing, etc.  A compari=
son of
the various approaches would be a very useful contribution.

  In summary, I think that the subject matter is an important one, and =
the
author is right to note the lack of an up-to-date textbook for asynchro=
nous
design.  I've suggested several ideas (mainly additions) that I believe=
 would
strengthen the book.  Of course, incorporating all of these suggestions=
 would
lead to a bloated text.  The ideal approach would be to encourage the a=
uthor to
persuade one of his colleagues at another institution to use a "beta" d=
raft of
the text in courses taught by someone other than the author. I expect t=
hat such
feedback would focus on the most important changes and would establish =
the value
of the text to a wider audience.


***********************************

Overall, these are positive reports which support my view that this is =
a timely
book with good potential. I hope you find them encouraging. I shall be
recommending to our editorial committee that you be offered a contract =
for the
book. In making that recommendation, it would be useful to hear your re=
action to
the referees' reviews. Reviewer 1 makes one substantial suggestion, whi=
le
reviewer 2 has several recommendations. I agree with a few of these (in=
cluding
more applications, for instance) but we should be careful to avoid lett=
ing the
book become too large, since that can make it very difficult to price s=
ensibly.

I look forward to hearing from you and again, thanks for your patience.=


